description.narrative: (Turkmenistan): In FY 2022 the Youth Development Activity (YDA) will focus on supporting youth from primary school through to their first jobs, to become productive, well-adjusted members of the Turkmen workforce and their communities. This activity blends education, entrepreneurship, civil society, and development initiatives to provide a holistic approach to supporting Turkmen youth. YDA will use FY 2022 funds to create opportunities for Turkmen youth to acquire marketable skills by arranging hard and soft skills courses at local educational organizations with a special focus on marginalized groups. It will assist training centers to make their curricula more market oriented and create sustainable linkages between educational organizations and industries. YDA will partner with local NGOs implement programs that support expiring youth in starting their own businesses and carrying out projects that contribute to economic development of their communities. YDA will utilize the USAID Youth in Development Policy and support areas that are critical to supporting Turkmen youth's educational needs. This activity will support ICS Mission Objective 1.2: Contribute to GoTM digitalization and modernization efforts to improve Turkmenistan's economy, government, and society by providing young entrepreneurs with the skills they need to succeed; thus, contributing to the economic stability and by empowering youth to be active civic leaders through training, and events. The activity will contribute to the U.S. Strategy on Central Asia Objective 1 by equipping youth with the critical thinking skills to recognize a clear path to maintaining individual sovereignty and achieving economic independence and Objective 6 by investing in a network of future leaders who will have the skills and knowledge to advocate for an enabling environment for business that is transparent, open, fair, and attractive to investors. This activity also supports CAATSA Objective 7: economic resilience.

description.narrative: This program provides an opportunity for young people in Turkmenistan to acquire practical skills in economics and entrepreneurship that help them to improve the quality of their lives and foster economic and social development. JA delivers participatory life planning, economic and business skills development programs that provide attitudes, skills, and knowledge to assist youth to contribute to Turkmenistans economic reform and development. Besides academic education, JA presents participants with practical experiences to apply business principles in a protected educational environment. These include hands-on experiences with board games and computer simulations in establishing companies, job shadow programs, international youth entrepreneurship competitions, etc. JA is educating the next generation of entrepreneurs, managers, and workers.

description.narrative: (Turkmenistan): USAID's Governance Support Program (GSP) contributes to improving the accountability, effectiveness, and transparency of government institutions. Turkmenistan continues to have limited exposure to international best practices. The government's inefficient implementation of its own priorities to advance e-governance, to provide equal opportunities in decision-making for all, including women and people with disabilities, as well as adherence to environmental safety measures, present an opening and an acceptance by the Government of Turkmenistan (GoTM) of the USAID-supported interventions in these areas. Eight years after an economic downturn that began in 2014, Turkmenistan is more open to foreign assistance than it has been in more than a decade and our bilateral relationship is better than it has been in years. With FY 2022 funds, the GSP will support increased information sharing among Turkmen government and non-government institutions and develop effective policies and legislation through public engagement. Beyond capacity development for civil servants, the activity will focus on several governance areas including but not limited to skills sets that civil servants need to keep up with the fast pace of changes in the targeted populations they aim to support and improve, e-governance, gender rights and accessibility, technical assistance in lawmaking, environmental governance and climate-friendly agricultural practices, and development strategies. By increasing the capacity of the Government of Turkmenistan and by sharing the American civil service model, USAID is building on the existing bilateral relationship to advance shared interests. This activity also supports ICS Mission Objective 4.1 via sharing best practices in delivering social services, and the U.S. Strategy for Central Asia objective 5: Promote rule of law reform and respect for human rights.

description.narrative: (Turkmenistan): .The Enriching Youth for Tomorrow activity aims to improve the capacity of youth to contribute to the local economy and community. EYFT delivers participatory life planning, economic and business skills development programs, which equip youth with the attitudes, skills and knowledge that will empower them to strive and thrive in the economy - guiding a new generation of Turkmen onto a clear path to fulfilling their aspirations and achieving economic independence by catalyzing on opportunities to work with future leaders of a free and prosperous world (NSS Pillar III). The activity will focus on workforce development as a key component to achieve this goal. With FY 2019 funds, USAID will utilize technologies that increase youth's access to information. USAID will engage stakeholders at the local, regional, and/or national level to develop youth-sensitive policies, processes, and services. The program will inform Turkmen youth of their rights, improve their leadership skills, and deliver training related to labor market needs. Workforce development activities will include internships, simulations, and vocational classes in economics and microenterprise development to improve competitiveness of youth in the labor market. The project will work with government institutions and private entities to assess job market needs and to induce adequate changes into legislation on vocational education specialization. The project also builds job skills of disabled youth and helps them find employment in the private sector. Through this activity, USAID is empowering youth to participate fully in civic and social activism, and thus strengthening the capacities of future leaders..

description.narrative: Improve the capacity of businesses to integrate into domestic and international markets through increases in productivity and improvements in corporate governance and the development and application of modern technology and marketing practices. Enhance the capacity of businesses and business associations in terms of their corporate governance capabilities and their application of best practices and technologies to achieve increased production and marketing of products and services.
